{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17608809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17608809"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:37:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:37:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16047"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16047"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.72,0.14,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8738"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8738"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16047"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49125"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"11188"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20896"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20898"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETeratogens are substances or environmental factors that can cause developmental abnormalities in a developing embryo or foetus. The effects of teratogens vary depending on the developmental stage at which exposure occurs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following gestational periods shows maximum susceptibility to teratogenic effects?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Weeks 0-2 post-conception","Weeks 3-8 post-conception","Weeks 9-17 post-conception","Weeks 18-26 post-conception","Weeks 27-38 post-conception"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe period of \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks 0-2 post-conception\u003C/strong\u003E typically follows an \u0022all-or-nothing\u0022 principle where severe damage results in miscarriage, while surviving embryos usually develop normally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWeeks 3-8 post-conception\u003C/strong\u003E represent the embryonic period when major organ systems are forming through rapid cell division and differentiation. This makes it the period of maximum teratogenic susceptibility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks 9-17 post-conception\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks 18-26 post-conception\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eweeks 27-38 post-conception\u003C/strong\u003E, the foetus is generally less susceptible to major structural abnormalities, though functional development of organs like the brain continues to be vulnerable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe timing of teratogenic exposure correlates with specific defects based on which structures are actively developing at that time. For example, neural tube defects are associated with exposures around weeks 3-4, while palate development is most vulnerable around weeks 6-9.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The embryonic period (weeks 3-8) has maximum susceptibility to teratogens due to rapid organ formation","Different organ systems have varying critical periods of development with peak susceptibility to teratogenic effects"],"references":["Alwan S, Chambers CD. Identifying Human Teratogens: An Update. J Pediatr Genet. 2015 Jun;4(2):39-41. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1556745. PMID: 27617116; PMCID: PMC4918715","Kaleelullah RA, Garugula N. Teratogenic Genesis in Fetal Malformations. Cureus. 2021 Feb 5;13(2):e13149. doi: 10.7759/cureus.13149. PMID: 33692919; PMCID: PMC7937350","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49125"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16047"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49125","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49125"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-22T11:05:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-22T11:06:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8738"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63686"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4935","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4935"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd5a",